{"title_page": "Seismic intensity scales", "text_new": "{{Earthquakes}}\n'''Seismic intensity scales''' categorize the intensity or severity of ground shaking (quaking) at a given location, such as resulting from an [[earthquake]]. They are distinguished from [[seismic magnitude scales]], which measure the magnitude or overall strength of an earthquake, which may, or perhaps not, cause perceptible shaking.\n\nIntensity scales are based on the observed effects of the shaking, such as the degree to which people or animals were alarmed, and the extent and severity of damage to different kinds of structures or natural features.  The maximal intensity observed, and the extent of the area where shaking was felt (see isoseismal map, below), can be used to estimate the location and magnitude of the source earthquake; this is especially useful for historical earthquakes where there is no instrumental record.\n\n==Ground shaking==\nGround shaking can be caused in various ways (volcanic tremors, avalanches, large explosions, etc.), but shaking intense enough to cause damage is usually due to rupturing of the earth's crust known as [[earthquakes]].  The intensity of shaking depends on several factors: \n* The \"size\" or strength of the source event, such as measured by various [[seismic magnitude scales]].\n* The type of [[seismic wave]] generated, and its orientation.\n* The depth of the event.\n* The distance from the source event.\n* [[Seismic site response|Site response]] due to local geology\nSite response is especially important as certain conditions, such as unconsolidated sediments in a basin, can amplify ground motions as much as ten times.\n\n[[File:1968 Illinois earthquake.svg|thumb|upright=1.6|left|Isoseismal map for the [[1968 Illinois earthquake]], showing the extent of different levels of shaking. The irregularity of areas is due to ground conditions and the underlying geology.]]\nWhere an earthquake is not recorded on seismographs an [[isoseismal map]] showing the intensities felt at different areas can be used to estimate the location and magnitude of the quake.<ref>{{Harvnb|Bormann|Wendt|Di Giacomo|2013|loc=\u00a73.1.2.1}}.</ref> Such maps are also useful for estimating the shaking intensity, and thereby the likely level of damage, to be expected from a future earthquake of similar magnitude. In Japan this kind of information is used when an earthquake occurs to anticipate the severity of damage to be expected in different areas.<ref>{{Harvnb|Doi|2010}}.</ref>\n\nThe intensity of local ground-shaking depends on several factors besides the magnitude of the earthquake,<ref>{{Harvnb|Bolt|1993|p=164 et seq.}}.</ref> one of the most important being soil conditions. For instance, thick layers of soft soil (such as fill) can amplify seismic waves, often at a considerable distance from the source, while sedimentary basins will often resonate, increasing the duration of shaking. This is why, in the [[1989 Loma Prieta earthquake]], the Marina district of [[San Francisco]] was one of the most damaged areas, though it was nearly 100&nbsp;km from the epicenter.<ref>{{Harvnb|Bolt|1993|pp=170\u2013171}}.</ref> Geological structures were also significant, such as where seismic waves passing under the south end of San Francisco Bay reflected off the base of the Earth's crust towards San Francisco and Oakland. A similar effect channeled seismic waves between the other major faults in the area.<ref>{{Harvnb|Bolt|1993|p=170}}.</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{Refimprove section|date=September 2008}}\nThe first simple classification of earthquake intensity was devised by Domenico Pignataro in the 1780s.<ref>{{cite book|title=Natural Disasters|author=David Alexander|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gWHsuGTcF34C&pg=PA28&lpg=PA28&dq=Domenico+Pignataro&source=bl&ots=KK1-lgBd0m&sig=l6DAPwlJqsbfNI_jbEqfLtTf-78&hl=en&sa=X&ei=nEhmT7PjFaKfiAK-9-yiDw&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Domenico%20Pignataro&f=false|page=28|publisher=[[Springer Science+Business Media]]|isbn=978-0-412-04741-1|year=1993|edition=First}}</ref>. The first recognisable intensity scale in the modern sense of the word was drawn up by P.N.G. Egen in 1828; it was ahead of its time.  However, The first modern mapping of an earthquake Intensities was made by [[Robert Mallet]], an Irish engineer who was sent by the Imperial College in London to make a research right after the [[(December) 1857 Basilicata Earthquake]], known also as [[The Great Neapolitan Earthquake of 1857]]. But The first widely adopted intensity scale, the ''[[Rossi\u2013Forel scale]]'', was introduced in the late 19th century It was a 10 grades scale. In 1902. an Italian [[seismologist]] named [[Giuseppe Mercalli]], created a new 12 grades scale named after his name. A very significant improvement was echived, mainly by [[Charles Francis Richter]] during the 50's, when (1) a correlation was found between seismic Intensity and the [[Peak ground acceleraton]] - PGA (watch the equation that Richter found for California) <ref><math>\\log a = \\frac{I}{3}-0.5</math> where <math>a</math> is the PGA for that given site with value of (cm/sec<sup>2</sup>) and <math>I</math> is the Intensity value for that site. see: Charles F. Richter., 1958. Elementary Seismology. Freeman & Company, San Francisco & London, (Chapter 11) p.140.</ref>. (2) a definition of the strength of the buildings, and a subdevision into groups (calld type of buildings) was made. Then, the evaluation of the seismic intensity was based upon the dammage grade to a given type of structure. That gave the Mercalli Scale the quantitative element, which reprisents the vulnerability of the building's type <ref>\n Lapajne, J., 1984. The MSK-78 Intensity Scale and Seismic Risk. Engineering Geology, 20:pp.105-112</ref>. Since then, that scale was called the [[Modified Mercali Intensity Scale]] - MMS and the evaluations of the Seismic Intensities became more reliable<ref>\n Bolt, B.A., Earthquakes, F&C, 1988, pp.146-152 </ref>.  \n\n\nSince then numerous intensity scales have been developed and are used in different parts of the world.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"clear: right;\"\n|-\n! Country/Region\n! Seismic intensity scale used\n|-\n| {{CHN}} || [[China Seismic Intensity Scale|Liedu scale]] (GB/T 17742-1999)\n|-\n| {{EUR}}|| [[European Macroseismic Scale]] (EMS-98)<ref name=\"GFZ\">\n{{cite web\n| url=http://www.gfz-potsdam.de/portal/gfz/Struktur/Departments/Department+2/sec26/projects/04_seismic_vulnerability_scales_risk/EMS-98/EMS-98_language_versions\n| title=The European Macroseismic Scale EMS-98\n| publisher=Centre Europ\u00e9en de G\u00e9odynamique et de S\u00e9ismologie (ECGS)\n| accessdate=2013-07-26\n}}\n</ref>\n|-\n| {{HKG}} || [[Mercalli intensity scale|Modified Mercalli scale]] (MM)<ref name=\"HK observatory\">\n{{cite web\n| url=http://www.weather.gov.hk/gts/equake/mag_and_int_e.htm\n| title=Magnitude and Intensity of an Earthquake\n| publisher=Hong Kong Observatory\n| accessdate=2008-09-15\n}}\n</ref>\n|-\n| {{IND}} || [[Medvedev\u2013Sponheuer\u2013Karnik scale]]\n|-\n| {{ISR}} || [[Medvedev\u2013Sponheuer\u2013Karnik scale]] (MSK-64)\n|-\n| {{JAP}} || [[Japan Meteorological Agency seismic intensity scale|JMA Seismic Intensity Scale]]\n|-\n| {{KAZ}} || [[Medvedev\u2013Sponheuer\u2013Karnik scale]] (MSK-64)\n|-\n| {{PHI}} || [[PHIVOLCS Earthquake Intensity Scale]] (PEIS)\n|-\n| {{RUS}} || [[Medvedev\u2013Sponheuer\u2013Karnik scale]] (MSK-64)\n|-\n| {{TWN}} || [[Central Weather Bureau Seismic Intensity Scale]]<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url=https://www.cwb.gov.tw/V7e/earthquake/quake_preparedness.htm\n| title=Earthquake Preparedness and Response\n| publisher=Central Weather Bureau\n| accessdate=2018-04-06\n}}\n</ref>\n|-\n| {{USA}} || [[Mercalli intensity scale|Modified Mercalli scale]] (MM)<ref name=\"USGS General Interest Publication\">\n{{cite web\n| url=http://pubs.usgs.gov/gip/earthq4/severitygip.html\n| title=The Severity of an Earthquake\n| publisher=U.S. Geological Survey\n| accessdate=2012-01-15\n}}\n</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Earthquake engineering]]\n* [[Peak ground acceleration]]\n* [[Seismic performance]]\n* [[Spectral acceleration]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|24em}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{bots|deny=Citation bot, BattyBot, BG19bot}}\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}} {{refbegin}}\n\n*{{Citation\n |last1= Bolt\n |first1= B. A.\n |year= 1993\n |title= Earthquakes and geological discovery\n |publisher= Scientific American Library\n |isbn= 0-7167-5040-6\n |url-access= registration\n |url= https://archive.org/details/earthquakesgeolo0000bolt\n }}.\n\n*{{Citation\n |first1= P. |last1= Bormann\n |first2= S. |last2= Wendt\n |first3= D. |last3= Di Giacomo\n |date= 2013\n |chapter= Chapter 3: Seismic Sources and Source Parameters\n |chapter-url= http://gfzpublic.gfz-potsdam.de/pubman/item/escidoc:108170:12/component/escidoc:364681/Chapter_3.pdf\n |editor1-last= Bormann\n |title= New Manual of Seismological Observatory Practice 2 (NMSOP-2)\n |doi= 10.2312/GFZ.NMSOP-2_ch3\n |url= http://bib.telegrafenberg.de/publizieren/vertrieb/nmsop/\n}}.\n\n*{{Citation\n |first1= K. |last1= Doi\n |date= 2010\n |title= Operational Procedures of Contributing Agencies\n |journal= Bulletin of the International Seismological Centre\n |volume= 47 |issue= 7\u201312 |pages= 25\n |issn= 2309-236X\n |url= ftp://isc-mirror.iris.washington.edu/pub/pdf/bulletin/summary/BulletinSummary20107_pub.pdf\n}}. Also available [http://www.isc.ac.uk/iscbulletin/agencies/JMA-ops.pdf here] (sections renumbered).\n\n\n{{refend}} {{div col end}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://earthquake.usgs.gov/data/shakemap/ USGS ShakeMap] Providing near-real-time maps of ground motion and shaking intensity following significant earthquakes.\n\n{{Seismic scales}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Seismic intensity scales}}\n[[Category:Seismic intensity scales]]\n[[Category:Seismology measurement]]\n[[Category:Seismology]]\n[[Category:Earthquake engineering]]\n", "text_old": "{{Earthquakes}}\n'''Seismic intensity scales''' categorize the intensity or severity of ground shaking (quaking) at a given location, such as resulting from an [[earthquake]]. They are distinguished from [[seismic magnitude scales]], which measure the magnitude or overall strength of an earthquake, which may, or perhaps not, cause perceptible shaking.\n\nIntensity scales are based on the observed effects of the shaking, such as the degree to which people or animals were alarmed, and the extent and severity of damage to different kinds of structures or natural features.  The maximal intensity observed, and the extent of the area where shaking was felt (see isoseismal map, below), can be used to estimate the location and magnitude of the source earthquake; this is especially useful for historical earthquakes where there is no instrumental record.\n\n==Ground shaking==\nGround shaking can be caused in various ways (volcanic tremors, avalanches, large explosions, etc.), but shaking intense enough to cause damage is usually due to rupturing of the earth's crust known as [[earthquakes]].  The intensity of shaking depends on several factors: \n* The \"size\" or strength of the source event, such as measured by various [[seismic magnitude scales]].\n* The type of [[seismic wave]] generated, and its orientation.\n* The depth of the event.\n* The distance from the source event.\n* [[Seismic site response|Site response]] due to local geology\nSite response is especially important as certain conditions, such as unconsolidated sediments in a basin, can amplify ground motions as much as ten times.\n\n[[File:1968 Illinois earthquake.svg|thumb|upright=1.6|left|Isoseismal map for the [[1968 Illinois earthquake]], showing the extent of different levels of shaking. The irregularity of areas is due to ground conditions and the underlying geology.]]\nWhere an earthquake is not recorded on seismographs an [[isoseismal map]] showing the intensities felt at different areas can be used to estimate the location and magnitude of the quake.<ref>{{Harvnb|Bormann|Wendt|Di Giacomo|2013|loc=\u00a73.1.2.1}}.</ref> Such maps are also useful for estimating the shaking intensity, and thereby the likely level of damage, to be expected from a future earthquake of similar magnitude. In Japan this kind of information is used when an earthquake occurs to anticipate the severity of damage to be expected in different areas.<ref>{{Harvnb|Doi|2010}}.</ref>\n\nThe intensity of local ground-shaking depends on several factors besides the magnitude of the earthquake,<ref>{{Harvnb|Bolt|1993|p=164 et seq.}}.</ref> one of the most important being soil conditions. For instance, thick layers of soft soil (such as fill) can amplify seismic waves, often at a considerable distance from the source, while sedimentary basins will often resonate, increasing the duration of shaking. This is why, in the [[1989 Loma Prieta earthquake]], the Marina district of [[San Francisco]] was one of the most damaged areas, though it was nearly 100&nbsp;km from the epicenter.<ref>{{Harvnb|Bolt|1993|pp=170\u2013171}}.</ref> Geological structures were also significant, such as where seismic waves passing under the south end of San Francisco Bay reflected off the base of the Earth's crust towards San Francisco and Oakland. A similar effect channeled seismic waves between the other major faults in the area.<ref>{{Harvnb|Bolt|1993|p=170}}.</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{Refimprove section|date=September 2008}}\nThe first simple classification of earthquake intensity was devised by Domenico Pignataro in the 1780s.<ref>{{cite book|title=Natural Disasters|author=David Alexander|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gWHsuGTcF34C&pg=PA28&lpg=PA28&dq=Domenico+Pignataro&source=bl&ots=KK1-lgBd0m&sig=l6DAPwlJqsbfNI_jbEqfLtTf-78&hl=en&sa=X&ei=nEhmT7PjFaKfiAK-9-yiDw&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Domenico%20Pignataro&f=false|page=28|publisher=[[Springer Science+Business Media]]|isbn=978-0-412-04741-1|year=1993|edition=First}}</ref>. The first recognisable intensity scale in the modern sense of the word was drawn up by P.N.G. Egen in 1828; it was ahead of its time.  However, The first modern mapping of an earthquake Intensities was made by [[Robert Mallet]], an Irish engineer who was sent by the Imperial College in London to make a research right after the [[(December) 1857 Basilicata Earthquake]], known also as [[The Great Neapolitan Earthquake of 1857]]. But The first widely adopted intensity scale, the ''[[Rossi\u2013Forel scale]]'', was introduced in the late 19th century It was a 10 grades scale. In 1902. an Italian [[seismologist]] named [[Giuseppe Mercalli]], created a new 12 grades scale named after his name. A very significant improvement was echived, mainly by [[Charles Francis Richter]] during the 50's, when (1) a correlation was found between seismic Intensity and the [[peak ground accelleraton]] - PGA (watch the equation that Richter found for California) <ref><math>\\log a = \\frac{I}{3}-0.5</math> where <math>a</math> is the PGA for that given site with value of (cm/sec<sup>2</sup>) and <math>I</math> is the Intensity value for that site. see: Charles F. Richter., 1958. Elementary Seismology. Freeman & Company, San Francisco & London, (Chapter 11) p.140.</ref>. (2) a definition of the strength of the buildings, and a subdevision into groups (calld type of buildings) was made. Then, the evaluation of the seismic intensity was based upon the dammage grade to a given type of structure. That gave the Mercalli Scale the quantitative element, which reprisents the vulnerability of the building's type <ref>\n Lapajne, J., 1984. The MSK-78 Intensity Scale and Seismic Risk. Engineering Geology, 20:pp.105-112</ref>. Since then, that scale was called the [[Modified Mercali Intensity Scale]] - MMS and the evaluations of the Seismic Intensities became more reliable<ref>\n Bolt, B.A., Earthquakes, F&C, 1988, pp.146-152 </ref>.  \n\n\nSince then numerous intensity scales have been developed and are used in different parts of the world.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"clear: right;\"\n|-\n! Country/Region\n! Seismic intensity scale used\n|-\n| {{CHN}} || [[China Seismic Intensity Scale|Liedu scale]] (GB/T 17742-1999)\n|-\n| {{EUR}}|| [[European Macroseismic Scale]] (EMS-98)<ref name=\"GFZ\">\n{{cite web\n| url=http://www.gfz-potsdam.de/portal/gfz/Struktur/Departments/Department+2/sec26/projects/04_seismic_vulnerability_scales_risk/EMS-98/EMS-98_language_versions\n| title=The European Macroseismic Scale EMS-98\n| publisher=Centre Europ\u00e9en de G\u00e9odynamique et de S\u00e9ismologie (ECGS)\n| accessdate=2013-07-26\n}}\n</ref>\n|-\n| {{HKG}} || [[Mercalli intensity scale|Modified Mercalli scale]] (MM)<ref name=\"HK observatory\">\n{{cite web\n| url=http://www.weather.gov.hk/gts/equake/mag_and_int_e.htm\n| title=Magnitude and Intensity of an Earthquake\n| publisher=Hong Kong Observatory\n| accessdate=2008-09-15\n}}\n</ref>\n|-\n| {{IND}} || [[Medvedev\u2013Sponheuer\u2013Karnik scale]]\n|-\n| {{ISR}} || [[Medvedev\u2013Sponheuer\u2013Karnik scale]] (MSK-64)\n|-\n| {{JAP}} || [[Japan Meteorological Agency seismic intensity scale|JMA Seismic Intensity Scale]]\n|-\n| {{KAZ}} || [[Medvedev\u2013Sponheuer\u2013Karnik scale]] (MSK-64)\n|-\n| {{PHI}} || [[PHIVOLCS Earthquake Intensity Scale]] (PEIS)\n|-\n| {{RUS}} || [[Medvedev\u2013Sponheuer\u2013Karnik scale]] (MSK-64)\n|-\n| {{TWN}} || [[Central Weather Bureau Seismic Intensity Scale]]<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url=https://www.cwb.gov.tw/V7e/earthquake/quake_preparedness.htm\n| title=Earthquake Preparedness and Response\n| publisher=Central Weather Bureau\n| accessdate=2018-04-06\n}}\n</ref>\n|-\n| {{USA}} || [[Mercalli intensity scale|Modified Mercalli scale]] (MM)<ref name=\"USGS General Interest Publication\">\n{{cite web\n| url=http://pubs.usgs.gov/gip/earthq4/severitygip.html\n| title=The Severity of an Earthquake\n| publisher=U.S. Geological Survey\n| accessdate=2012-01-15\n}}\n</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Earthquake engineering]]\n* [[Peak ground acceleration]]\n* [[Seismic performance]]\n* [[Spectral acceleration]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|24em}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{bots|deny=Citation bot, BattyBot, BG19bot}}\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}} {{refbegin}}\n\n*{{Citation\n |last1= Bolt\n |first1= B. A.\n |year= 1993\n |title= Earthquakes and geological discovery\n |publisher= Scientific American Library\n |isbn= 0-7167-5040-6\n |url-access= registration\n |url= https://archive.org/details/earthquakesgeolo0000bolt\n }}.\n\n*{{Citation\n |first1= P. |last1= Bormann\n |first2= S. |last2= Wendt\n |first3= D. |last3= Di Giacomo\n |date= 2013\n |chapter= Chapter 3: Seismic Sources and Source Parameters\n |chapter-url= http://gfzpublic.gfz-potsdam.de/pubman/item/escidoc:108170:12/component/escidoc:364681/Chapter_3.pdf\n |editor1-last= Bormann\n |title= New Manual of Seismological Observatory Practice 2 (NMSOP-2)\n |doi= 10.2312/GFZ.NMSOP-2_ch3\n |url= http://bib.telegrafenberg.de/publizieren/vertrieb/nmsop/\n}}.\n\n*{{Citation\n |first1= K. |last1= Doi\n |date= 2010\n |title= Operational Procedures of Contributing Agencies\n |journal= Bulletin of the International Seismological Centre\n |volume= 47 |issue= 7\u201312 |pages= 25\n |issn= 2309-236X\n |url= ftp://isc-mirror.iris.washington.edu/pub/pdf/bulletin/summary/BulletinSummary20107_pub.pdf\n}}. Also available [http://www.isc.ac.uk/iscbulletin/agencies/JMA-ops.pdf here] (sections renumbered).\n\n\n{{refend}} {{div col end}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://earthquake.usgs.gov/data/shakemap/ USGS ShakeMap] Providing near-real-time maps of ground motion and shaking intensity following significant earthquakes.\n\n{{Seismic scales}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Seismic intensity scales}}\n[[Category:Seismic intensity scales]]\n[[Category:Seismology measurement]]\n[[Category:Seismology]]\n[[Category:Earthquake engineering]]\n", "name_user": "Ronavni", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seismic_intensity_