{"title_page": "Uttarakhand Kranti Dal", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2016}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{Refimprove|date=November 2012}}\n{{original research|date=March 2012}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox Indian Political Party \n|  party_name     = Uttarakhand Kranti Dal\n|abbreviation      = UKD\n|  party_logo     = [[File:UKD-flag.gif|200px]]\n|  colorcode      = {{Uttarakhand Kranti Dal/meta/color}}\n|  leader = [[Kashi Singh Airy]]\n|  president = [[Kashi Singh Airy]]\n|  loksabha_leader = \n|  rajyasabha_leader =  \n|  foundation     = {{Start date and years ago|df=yes|p=y|1979|07|26}}\n| founder = \n*[[Bipin Chandra Tripathi]]\n*[[D. D. Pant]]\n*[[Indramani Badoni]]\n*[[Kashi Singh Airy]]\n| headquarters = Kranti Bhavan, 10 Court Road, [[Dehradun]]-248001, [[Uttarakhand]]\n|  ideology = [[Regionalism (politics)|Regionalism]]<br>[[Protectionism]]<br>[[Civic nationalism]]<br>[[Democratic socialism]]\n| colours           = {{colour box|{{Uttarakhand Kranti Dal/meta/color}}}} [[Myrtle green]]\n| position = [[Centre-Right politics|Centre-Right]] to [[right wing|Right-wing]]\n| state_seats_name = [[Uttarakhand Legislative Assembly]]\n| state_seats = {{Composition bar|0|71|hex={{Uttarakhand Kranti Dal/meta/color}}}}\n| symbol            = [[File:Indian Election Symbol Chair.png|150px]]\n| website = [http://www.uttarakhandkrantidal.in www.uttarakhandkrantidal.in]\n|eci= [[List of political parties in India|Registered Unrecognised Party]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Uttarakhand Kranti Dal''' ([[translation]]: '''Uttarakhand Revolutionary Party'''; {{small|abbr.}} '''UKD'''), is a registered unrecognised regional [[political party]] in [[Uttarakhand]], [[India]]. It bills itself as the only regional party of the Uttarakhand in contrast to the national parties that dominate the state's politics.\n\nIn the present [[Uttarakhand Legislative Assembly]], elected in 2017, it does not have any member as compared with one member in the previous 2012, three members in 2007 and four members in 2002 assembly elections of the state.<ref>[[2017 Uttarakhand Legislative Assembly election]]</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{main|Uttarakhand movement}}\n\nThe UKD was established on 26 July 1979 by [[Bipin Chandra Tripathi]], Dr. [[D. D. Pant]], [[Indramani Badoni]]\nand [[Kashi Singh Airy]] at [[Nanital]] to fight for a separate state composed of the hill districts of [[Uttar Pradesh]]. The founding convention was chaired by Dr. D. D. Pant, former vice-chancellor of [[Kumaon University]]. Under the young leadership of Kashi Singh Airy who took the charge of struggle and public agitation and the aim was finally achieved, when the separate ''Uttaranchal'' state was formed on 9 November 2000, later renamed [[Uttarakhand]] in 2007. However, in the first ever state assembly elections in 2002, the party won only four out of 70 seats, and was outmaneuvered by the [[Indian National Congress]] and [[Bharatiya Janata Party]], both despite being late comers to the separate state movement, succeeded in capturing its momentum for electoral gain and formed governments in the state {{Citation needed|date=July 2009}}\n\nSo far, the UKD has not been able to achieve its ostensible goal in establishing a viable ''[[Third party (politics)|third force]]'' in Uttarakhand politics due to splits and divisions within its ranks. However, it maintains friendly relations with left parties in the state such as the [[Communist Party of India]], [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)]], [[Communist Party of India (Marxist\u2013Leninist) Liberation]] and the other minor parties and social movements in Uttarakhand.\n\nThe party has taken on various campaigns in the past geared towards the social and economic upliftment of the [[Pahari people]]. The party has however embraced a number of causes of concern to the diversity of people living in Uttarakhand, defining the ''Uttarakhandi'' identity in broad and inclusive terms. As such, its ideology of civic as opposed to ethnic nationalism can be compared to other [[centre-left]] nationalist parties like the [[Scottish National Party]] or [[Plaid Cymru]], although its orientation and goals are emphatically non-secessionist.\n\n==Leadership==\nThe party's current face is [[Kashi Singh Airy]], a prominent leader of the Uttarakhand statehood movement and a senior leader of Uttarakhand Kranti Dal, who was elected for [[Uttar Pradesh Legislative Assembly]] three times (1985\u20131989, 1989\u20131991, 1993\u20131996) and was elected for first [[Uttarakhand Legislative Assembly]]. [[Diwakar Bhatt]] is the current president of UKD, with Kashi Singh Airy and Dr. [[Narayan Singh Jantwal]] as honorary presidents, vice president are [[A. P. Juyal]], [[Bhuwan Chandra Joshi]], [[Beena Bahuguna]] and [[Pushpesh Tripathi]]\u2014senior statehood activists and prominent faces of Uttarakhand statehood movement who fought from the forefront in the creation of Uttarakhand state. Beena Bahuguna is now elected as a Block Pramukh of [[Raipur, Uttarakhand|Raipur]], [[Dehradun]]. [[Jaswant Singh Bisht]] was the first elected [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (India)|MLA]] of the party from [[Ranikhet (Uttarakhand Assembly constituency)|Ranikhet]] constituency. Other personalities include late [[Indramani Badoni]] and late [[Bipin Chandra Tripathi]] were the founding members and long time agitators for the separate state movement.\n\n== Factionism and decline ==\n{{Main|3rd Uttarakhand Assembly}}\nIn the [[2012 Uttarakhand Legislative Assembly election|2012 Uttarakhand Assembly election]], Uttarakhand Kranti Dal contested as '''Uttarakhand Kranti Dal (P)''' led by then party president [[Trivendra Singh Panwar]]. The original party name and the election symbol (chair) was frozen by the [[Election Commission of India]] following the factionism and leadership dispute within the party that led to its breakup.\nThe splinter group '''Uttarakhand Kranti Dal (D)''' led by former [[Member of the  Legislative Assembly (India)|MLA]] and [[Uttarakhand Council of Ministers|Cabinet Minister]] in the [[First Khanduri ministry|Khanduri government]] and later [[Pokhriyal ministry|Pokhriyal government]], [[Diwakar Bhatt]] broke away from the UKD with his supporters claiming the original party leadership.\n[[Pritam Singh Panwar]] was the only winning candidate of the party in the 2012 Assembly election, who ran under the UKD(P) banner.\n\nUttarakhand Kranti Dal's original name and party symbol was restored in 2017 with the merger of both groups.\n\nThe party's performance in various assembly and parliamentary elections has been on consistent decline. The main reasons cited for UKD's decline in the politics of Uttarakhand are; inner factionism, loss of voter base to other parties and frequent switching for power share between the BJP and Congress governments, which is often viewed negatively as a political opportunism.\n\n== Electoral performance in Uttarakhand==\n{{Main|Elections in Uttarakhand}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Legislature !! Party leader !! Seats won !! Change in seats !! Outcome\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[2002 Uttarakhand Legislative Assembly election|2002]] || [[1st Uttarakhand Assembly|1st Vidhan Sabha]] || rowspan=\"2\"|[[Bipin Chandra Tripathi]] || {{Composition bar|4|70|{{Uttarakhand Kranti Dal/meta/color}}}} || {{increase}} 4 || {{no2|Opposition}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[2004 Indian general election in Uttarakhand|2004]] || [[14th Lok Sabha]] || {{Composition bar|0|5|{{Uttarakhand Kranti Dal/meta/color}}}} || {{nochange}} || \u2013\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[2007 Uttarakhand Legislative Assembly election|2007]] || [[2nd Uttarakhand Assembly|2nd Vidhan Sabha]] || rowspan=\"2\"|[[Diwakar Bhatt]] || {{Composition bar|3|70|{{Uttarakhand Kranti Dal/meta/color}}}} || {{decrease}} 1 || {{yes2|Government with [[Bharatiya Janata Party|BJP]]}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[2009 Indian general election in Uttarakhand|2009]] || [[15th Lok Sabha]] || {{Composition bar|0|5|{{Uttarakhand Kranti Dal/meta/color}}}} || {{nochange}} || \u2013\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[2012 Uttarakhand Legislative Assembly election|2012]] || [[3rd Uttarakhand Assembly|3rd Vidhan Sabha]] || rowspan=\"2\"|[[Trivendra Singh Panwar]] || {{Composition bar|1|70|{{Uttarakhand Kranti Dal/meta/color}}}} || {{decrease}} 2 || {{yes2|Government with [[Indian National Congress|INC]]}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[2014 Indian general election in Uttarakhand|2014]] || [[16th Lok Sabha]] || {{Composition bar|0|5|{{Uttarakhand Kranti Dal/meta/color}}}} || {{nochange}} || rowspan=\"3\"| \u2013\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[2017 Uttarakhand Legislative Assembly election|2017]] || [[4th Uttarakhand Assembly|4th Vidhan Sabha]] || rowspan=\"2\"|[[Kashi Singh Airy]] || {{Composition bar|0|70|{{Uttarakhand Kranti Dal/meta/color}}}} || {{decrease}} 1\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[2019 Indian general election in Uttarakhand|2019]]\n|| [[17th Lok Sabha]] || {{Composition bar|0|5|{{Uttarakhand Kranti Dal/meta/color}}}} || {{nochange}}\n|}\n\n== See also==\n{{Portal|Socialism|Politics|India|}}\n\n*[[Revolutionary Party]]\n*[[List of socialist parties]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.uttarakhandkrantidal.in/ Official Website of Uttarakhand Kranti Dal]\n*[http://www.ukd.prayaga.org A website established by UKD supporters].\n*[http://www.merapahadforum.com/uttarakhand-at-a-glance/ukd-regional-party/ \u0909\u0924\u094d\u0924\u0930\u093e\u0916\u0923\u094d\u0921 \u0915\u094d\u0930\u093e\u0928\u094d\u0924\u093f \u0926\u0932 \u0915\u093e \u0907\u0924\u093f\u0939\u093e\u0938]\n*[http://video.google.com/videoplay?docid=-9079295700345172271&q=bipin+tripathi&total=1&start=0&num=10&so=0&type=search&plindex=0 A video of UKD public meeting]\n*[http://uttarakhand.org/library Uttarakhand Solidarity Network Web Portal Library]\n*[http://www.allindoon.com/index.php/newsarticle?view=showelectionarticle&id=3216 allindoon.com]\n*[http://legalassistanceforum.org/event/event18.html legalassistanceforum.org]  \n*[http://www.lawcollegedehradun.com/debate_society.htm lawcollegedehradun.com]\n*[http://www.garhwalpost.com/article/Dehradun/11063/1/print/ garhwalpost.com]\n\n{{Indian political parties}}\n\n[[Category:Political parties established in 1979]]\n[[Category:Political parties in Uttarakhand]]\n[[Category:Regionalist parties in India]]\n[[Category:Political parties in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2016}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{Refimprove|date=November 2012}}\n{{original research|date=March 2012}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox Indian Political Party \n|  party_name     = Uttarakhand Kranti Dal\n|abbreviation      = UKD\n|  party_logo     = [[File:UKD-flag.gif|200px]]\n|  colorcode      = {{Uttarakhand Kranti Dal/meta/color}}\n|  leader = [[Kashi Singh Airy]]\n|  president = [[Kashi Singh Airy]]\n|  loksabha_leader = \n|  rajyasabha_leader =  \n|  foundation     = {{Start date and years ago|df=yes|p=y|1979|07|26}}\n| founder = \n*[[Bipin Chandra Tripathi]]\n*[[D. D. Pant]]\n*[[Indramani Badoni]]\n*[[Kashi Singh Airy]]\n| headquarters = Kranti Bhavan, 10 Court Road, [[Dehradun]]-248001, [[Uttarakhand]]\n|  ideology = [[Regionalism (politics)|Regionalism]]<br>[[Protectionism]]<br>[[Civic nationalism]]<br>[[Democratic socialism]]\n| colours           = {{colour box|{{Uttarakhand Kranti Dal/meta/color}}}} [[Myrtle green]]\n| position = [[Centre-left politics|Centre-left]] to [[Left-wing politics|left-wing]]\n| state_seats_name = [[Uttarakhand Legislative Assembly]]\n| alliance = [[Progressive Democratic Front (Uttarakhand)|Progress Democratic Front]] (PDF)\n| state_seats = {{Composition bar|0|71|hex={{Uttarakhand Kranti Dal/meta/color}}}}\n| symbol            = [[File:Indian Election Symbol Chair.png|150px]]\n| website = [http://www.uttarakhandkrantidal.in www.uttarakhandkrantidal.in]\n|eci= [[List of political parties in India|Registered Unrecognised Party]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Uttarakhand Kranti Dal''' ([[translation]]: '''Uttarakhand Revolutionary Party'''; {{small|abbr.}} '''UKD'''), is a registered unrecognised regional [[political party]] in [[Uttarakhand]], [[India]]. It bills itself as the only regional party of the Uttarakhand in contrast to the national parties that dominate the state's politics.\n\nIn the present [[Uttarakhand Legislative Assembly]], elected in 2017, it does not have any member as compared with one member in the previous 2012, three members in 2007 and four members in 2002 assembly elections of the state.<ref>[[2017 Uttarakhand Legislative Assembly election]]</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{main|Uttarakhand movement}}\n\nThe UKD was established on 26 July 1979 by [[Bipin Chandra Tripathi]], Dr. [[D. D. Pant]], [[Indramani Badoni]]\nand [[Kashi Singh Airy]] at [[Nanital]] to fight for a separate state composed of the hill districts of [[Uttar Pradesh]]. The founding convention was chaired by Dr. D. D. Pant, former vice-chancellor of [[Kumaon University]]. Under the young leadership of Kashi Singh Airy who took the charge of struggle and public agitation and the aim was finally achieved, when the separate ''Uttaranchal'' state was formed on 9 November 2000, later renamed [[Uttarakhand]] in 2007. However, in the first ever state assembly elections in 2002, the party won only four out of 70 seats, and was outmaneuvered by the [[Indian National Congress]] and [[Bharatiya Janata Party]], both despite being late comers to the separate state movement, succeeded in capturing its momentum for electoral gain and formed governments in the state {{Citation needed|date=July 2009}}\n\nSo far, the UKD has not been able to achieve its ostensible goal in establishing a viable ''[[Third party (politics)|third force]]'' in Uttarakhand politics due to splits and divisions within its ranks. However, it maintains friendly relations with left parties in the state such as the [[Communist Party of India]], [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)]], [[Communist Party of India (Marxist\u2013Leninist) Liberation]] and the other minor parties and social movements in Uttarakhand.\n\nThe party has taken on various campaigns in the past geared towards the social and economic upliftment of the [[Pahari people]]. The party has however embraced a number of causes of concern to the diversity of people living in Uttarakhand, defining the ''Uttarakhandi'' identity in broad and inclusive terms. As such, its ideology of civic as opposed to ethnic nationalism can be compared to other [[centre-left]] nationalist parties like the [[Scottish National Party]] or [[Plaid Cymru]], although its orientation and goals are emphatically non-secessionist.\n\n==Leadership==\nThe party's current face is [[Kashi Singh Airy]], a prominent leader of the Uttarakhand statehood movement and a senior leader of Uttarakhand Kranti Dal, who was elected for [[Uttar Pradesh Legislative Assembly]] three times (1985\u20131989, 1989\u20131991, 1993\u20131996) and was elected for first [[Uttarakhand Legislative Assembly]]. [[Diwakar Bhatt]] is the current president of UKD, with Kashi Singh Airy and Dr. [[Narayan Singh Jantwal]] as honorary presidents, vice president are [[A. P. Juyal]], [[Bhuwan Chandra Joshi]], [[Beena Bahuguna]] and [[Pushpesh Tripathi]]\u2014senior statehood activists and prominent faces of Uttarakhand statehood movement who fought from the forefront in the creation of Uttarakhand state. Beena Bahuguna is now elected as a Block Pramukh of [[Raipur, Uttarakhand|Raipur]], [[Dehradun]]. [[Jaswant Singh Bisht]] was the first elected [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (India)|MLA]] of the party from [[Ranikhet (Uttarakhand Assembly constituency)|Ranikhet]] constituency. Other personalities include late [[Indramani Badoni]] and late [[Bipin Chandra Tripathi]] were the founding members and long time agitators for the separate state movement.\n\n== Factionism and decline ==\n{{Main|3rd Uttarakhand Assembly}}\nIn the [[2012 Uttarakhand Legislative Assembly election|2012 Uttarakhand Assembly election]], Uttarakhand Kranti Dal contested as '''Uttarakhand Kranti Dal (P)''' led by then party president [[Trivendra Singh Panwar]]. The original party name and the election symbol (chair) was frozen by the [[Election Commission of India]] following the factionism and leadership dispute within the party that led to its breakup.\nThe splinter group '''Uttarakhand Kranti Dal (D)''' led by former [[Member of the  Legislative Assembly (India)|MLA]] and [[Uttarakhand Council of Ministers|Cabinet Minister]] in the [[First Khanduri ministry|Khanduri government]] and later [[Pokhriyal ministry|Pokhriyal government]], [[Diwakar Bhatt]] broke away from the UKD with his supporters claiming the original party leadership.\n[[Pritam Singh Panwar]] was the only winning candidate of the party in the 2012 Assembly election, who ran under the UKD(P) banner.\n\nUttarakhand Kranti Dal's original name and party symbol was restored in 2017 with the merger of both groups.\n\nThe party's performance in various assembly and parliamentary elections has been on consistent decline. The main reasons cited for UKD's decline in the politics of Uttarakhand are; inner factionism, loss of voter base to other parties and frequent switching for power share between the BJP and Congress governments, which is often viewed negatively as a political opportunism.\n\n== Electoral performance in Uttarakhand==\n{{Main|Elections in Uttarakhand}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Legislature !! Party leader !! Seats won !! Change in seats !! Outcome\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[2002 Uttarakhand Legislative Assembly election|2002]] || [[1st Uttarakhand Assembly|1st Vidhan Sabha]] || rowspan=\"2\"|[[Bipin Chandra Tripathi]] || {{Composition bar|4|70|{{Uttarakhand Kranti Dal/meta/color}}}} || {{increase}} 4 || {{no2|Opposition}}\n|- style=\"text-align:cen