lished by UKD supporters].\n*[http://www.merapahadforum.com/uttarakhand-at-a-glance/ukd-regional-party/ \u0909\u0924\u094d\u0924\u0930\u093e\u0916\u0923\u094d\u0921 \u0915\u094d\u0930\u093e\u0928\u094d\u0924\u093f \u0926\u0932 \u0915\u093e \u0907\u0924\u093f\u0939\u093e\u0938]\n*[http://video.google.com/videoplay?docid=-9079295700345172271&q=bipin+tripathi&total=1&start=0&num=10&so=0&type=search&plindex=0 A video of UKD public meeting]\n*[http://uttarakhand.org/library Uttarakhand Solidarity Network Web Portal Library]\n*[http://www.allindoon.com/index.php/newsarticle?view=showelectionarticle&id=3216 allindoon.com]\n*[http://legalassistanceforum.org/event/event18.html legalassistanceforum.org]  \n*[http://www.lawcollegedehradun.com/debate_society.htm lawcollegedehradun.com]\n*[http://www.garhwalpost.com/article/Dehradun/11063/1/print/ garhwalpost.com]\n\n{{Indian political parties}}\n\n[[Category:Political parties established in 1979]]\n[[Category:Political parties in Uttarakhand]]\n[[Category:Regionalist parties in India]]\n[[Category:Political parties in India]]\n", "name_user": "Shankardutt", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uttarakhand_Kranti_Dal"}
{"title_page": "Antonio Paganin", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Antonio Paganin\n| fullname = \n| image = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1966|6|18|df=yes}} \n| birth_place = [[Vicenza]], Italy\n| height = 1.82 m\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = 1982\u20131984\n| years2 = 1984\u20131988\n| years3 = 1988\u20131990\n| years4 = 1990\u20131995\n| years5 = 1995\u20131996\n| years6 = 1996\u20131997\n| years7 = 1997\u20131999\n| years8 = 1999\u20132003\n| clubs1 = [[Bologna F.C. 1909|Bologna]]\n| clubs2 = [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]]\n| clubs3 = [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]]\n| clubs4 = [[F.C. Internazionale Milano|Internazionale]]\n| clubs5 = [[Atalanta B.C.|Atalanta]]\n| clubs6 = [[Hellas Verona F.C.|Verona]]\n| clubs7 = Torri Quartesolo\n| clubs8 = [[U.C. Montecchio Maggiore|Montecchio Maggiore]]\n| caps1 = 0\n| caps2 = 46\n| caps3 = 53\n| caps4 = 109\n| caps5 = 27\n| caps6 = 11\n| caps7 = \n| goals1 = 0\n| goals2 = 1\n| goals3 = 1\n| goals4 = 0\n| goals5 = 0\n| goals6 = 0\n| goals7 = \n| manageryears1 = \n| managerclubs1 = \n}}\n\n'''Antonio Paganin''' (born 18 June 1966) is an Italian former professional [[Association football|football]] player, who played as a [[Defender (association football)|defender]]. He is the brother of [[Massimo Paganin]], who was also a football player.\n\n==Career==\nPaganin was born in [[Vicenza]]. He began his career with [[Bologna F.C. 1909|Bologna]] (1982\u20131984) in the lower divisions, later moving to [[Serie A]] club [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]] (1984\u201388), and winning two [[Coppa Italia]] trophies during his time with the club. He moved to [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]] for two seasons (1988\u201390), helping the team to earn [[Serie A]] promotion, before moving to [[F.C. Internazionale Milano|Internazionale]] (1990\u201395), where he won the [[UEFA Cup]] twice, in 1991 and in 1994. He later played with [[Atalanta B.C.|Atalanta]] (1995\u201396), and [[Hellas Verona F.C.|Verona]]  (1996\u201397), where he concluded his [[Serie A]] career, before moving to Torri Quartesolo  (1997\u201399), and later ending his career with [[U.C. Montecchio Maggiore|Montecchio Maggiore]] (1999\u20132003), in the lower divisions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legaseriea.it/it/serie-a-tim/calciatore?p_p_id=BDC_dettaglio_calciatore_WAR_LegaCalcioBDC&p_p_lifecycle=0&p_p_state=normal&p_p_mode=view&p_p_col_id=column-1&p_p_col_pos=1&p_p_col_count=2&_BDC_dettaglio_calciatore_WAR_LegaCalcioBDC_idPersona=4539 |title=Antonio Paganin |website=legaseriea.it |language=Italian |accessdate=29 April 2015 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttocalciatori.net/Paganin_Antonio|title=Antonio Paganin|website=tuttocalciatori.net|language=Italian|accessdate=29 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n'''Inter'''\n* [[UEFA Cup]]: [[1990\u201391 UEFA Cup|1990\u201391]], [[1993\u201394 UEFA Cup|1993\u201394]].\n\n'''Sampdoria'''\n* [[Coppa Italia]]: [[1984\u201385 Coppa Italia|1984\u201385]], [[1987\u201388 Coppa Italia|1987\u201388]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Paganin, Antonio}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Vicenza]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Italian footballers]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:Serie B players]]\n[[Category:Bologna F.C. 1909 players]]\n[[Category:U.C. Sampdoria players]]\n[[Category:Udinese Calcio players]]\n[[Category:Inter Milan players]]\n[[Category:Atalanta B.C. players]]\n[[Category:Hellas Verona F.C. players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Cup winning players]]\n\n\n{{Italy-footy-defender-1960s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name= Antonio Paganin\n| fullname = \n| image = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1966|6|18|df=yes}} \n| birth_place = [[Vicenza]], [[Italy]]\n| height = {{height|m=1.82}}\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = 1982\u20131984 \n| years2 = 1984\u20131988 \n| years3 = 1988\u20131990 \n| years4 = 1990\u20131995 \n| years5 = 1995\u20131996 \n| years6 = 1996\u20131997 \n| years7 = 1997\u20131999 \n| years8 = 1999\u20132003\n| clubs1 = [[Bologna F.C. 1909|Bologna]] \n| clubs2 = [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]] \n| clubs3 = [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]] \n| clubs4 = [[F.C. Internazionale Milano|Internazionale]] \n| clubs5 = [[Atalanta B.C.|Atalanta]] \n| clubs6 = [[Hellas Verona F.C.|Verona]] \n| clubs7 = Torri Quartesolo \n| clubs8 = [[U.C. Montecchio Maggiore|Montecchio Maggiore]]\n| caps1 = 0  \n| caps2 = 46  \n| caps3 = 53  \n| caps4 = 109  \n| caps5 = 27  \n| caps6 = 11  \n| caps7 = \n| goals1 = 0  \n| goals2 = 1  \n| goals3 = 1  \n| goals4 = 0  \n| goals5 = 0  \n| goals6 = 0  \n| goals7 = \n| nationalyears1 = \n| nationalteam1 = \n| nationalcaps1 = \n| nationalgoals1 = \n| manageryears1 = \n| managerclubs1 = \n| pcupdate = \n| ntupdate =\n}}\n\n'''Antonio Paganin''' (born 18 June 1966, in [[Vicenza]]) is a retired [[Italy|Italian]] professional [[Association football|football]] player, who played as a [[Defender (association football)|defender]]. He is the brother of [[Massimo Paganin]], who was also a football player.\n\n==Career==\nPaganin began his career with [[Bologna F.C. 1909|Bologna]] (1982\u20131984) in the lower divisions, later moving to [[Serie A]] club [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]] (1984\u201388), and winning two [[Coppa Italia]] trophies during his time with the club. He moved to [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]] for two seasons (1988\u201390), helping the team to earn [[Serie A]] promotion, before moving to [[F.C. Internazionale Milano|Internazionale]] (1990\u201395), where he won the [[UEFA Cup]] twice, in 1991 and in 1994. He later played with [[Atalanta B.C.|Atalanta]] (1995\u201396), and [[Hellas Verona F.C.|Verona]]  (1996-97), where he concluded his [[Serie A]] career, before moving to Torri Quartesolo  (1997\u201399), and later ending his career with [[U.C. Montecchio Maggiore|Montecchio Maggiore]] (1999-2003), in the lower divisions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legaseriea.it/it/serie-a-tim/calciatore?p_p_id=BDC_dettaglio_calciatore_WAR_LegaCalcioBDC&p_p_lifecycle=0&p_p_state=normal&p_p_mode=view&p_p_col_id=column-1&p_p_col_pos=1&p_p_col_count=2&_BDC_dettaglio_calciatore_WAR_LegaCalcioBDC_idPersona=4539 |title=Antonio Paganin |website=legaseriea.it |language=Italian |accessdate=29 April 2015 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttocalciatori.net/Paganin_Antonio|title=Antonio Paganin|website=tuttocalciatori.net|language=Italian|accessdate=29 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n;[[Internazionale Milano F.C.|Inter]]\n* [[UEFA Cup]] winner: [[1990\u201391 UEFA Cup|1990\u201391]], [[1993\u201394 UEFA Cup|1993\u201394]].\n\n;[[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]]\n* [[Coppa Italia]] winner: [[1984\u201385 Coppa Italia|1984\u201385]], [[1987\u201388 Coppa Italia|1987\u201388]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Paganin, Antonio}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian footballers]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:Serie B players]]\n[[Category:Bologna F.C. 1909 players]]\n[[Category:U.C. Sampdoria players]]\n[[Category:Udinese Calcio players]]\n[[Category:Inter Milan players]]\n[[Category:Atalanta B.C. players]]\n[[Category:Hellas Verona F.C. players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Cup winning players]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Vicenza]]\n\n\n{{Italy-footy-defender-1960s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Robby.is.on", "label": "safe", "comment": "Move place of birth out of lede per Manuel of Style. Minor corrections.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antonio_Paganin"}
{"title_page": "Lucila Pascua", "text_new": "{{spanish name 2|Pascua|Su\u00e1rez}} \n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name               = Lucila Pascua\n| image              = Lucila Pascua.JPG\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Lucila Pascua in a game with [[CB Conquero]]\n| number             = 13\n| position           = [[Center (basketball)|Center]]\n| height_m           = 1.96\n| height_ft          = 6\n| height_in          = 5\n| league             = [[Liga Femenina de Baloncesto|Liga Femenina]]\n| team               = AE Sedis B\u00e0squet\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1983|3|21}}\n| birth_place        = [[Ripollet]], Spain\n| nationality        = Spanish\n| career_start       = 2001 \n| career_end         = \n| years1             = 2001\u20132005 \n| team1              = [[CDB Zaragoza|Mann Filter Zaragoza]]\n| years2             = 2005\u20132009 \n| team2              = [[CB San Jos\u00e9 Le\u00f3n]]\n| years3             = 2009\u20132011 \n| team3              = [[CDB Zaragoza|Mann Filter Zaragoza]]\n| years4             = 2011\u20132013 \n| team4              = [[CB Avenida|Perfumer\u00edas Avenida Salamanca]]\n| years5             = 2013\u20132014 \n| team5              = [[\u017dKK Novi Zagreb]]\n| years6             = 2013\u20132014 \n| team6              = [[PINKK-P\u00e9csi 424]]\n| years7             = 2014\u20132016\n| team7              = [[CB Conquero]]\n| years8             = 2016\u20132018\n| team8              = [[Stadium Casablanca|Mann-Filter]]\n| years9             = 2018\u20132019\n| team9              = [[Gernika KESB|Lointek Gernika Bizkaia]]\n| years10            = 2019-present\n| team10             = [[AE Sedis B\u00e0squet]]\n| highlights         = \n*[[Liga Femenina de Baloncesto|Spanish League]] champion (2013)\n*2x [[Copa de la Reina de Baloncesto|Spanish Cup]] champion (2012, 2016)\n*2x [[Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a de Baloncesto Femenino|Spanish Supercup]] champion (2012, 2013)\n*[[Nemzeti Bajnoks\u00e1g I/A (women's basketball)|Hungarian League]] champion (2014)\n*[[2011 FIBA Europe SuperCup Women|European SuperCup]] champion (2011)\n| medaltemplates     = \n{{MedalCountry|{{bkw|ESP}}}}\n{{MedalOlympic}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Rio de Janeiro]]|[[Basketball at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|Team]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA Women's Basketball World Cup|World Championship]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2014 FIBA World Championship for Women|2014 Turkey]]|}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2010 FIBA World Championship for Women|2010 Czech Republic]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[EuroBasket Women|EuroBasket]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[Eurobasket 2007 Women|2007 Italy]]|}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[Eurobasket 2003 Women|2003 Greece]]|}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[Eurobasket 2005 Women|2005 Turkey]]|}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[Eurobasket 2009 Women|2009 Latvia]]|}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[EuroBasket Women 2015|2015 Hungary/Romania]]|}}\n}}\n'''Lucila Pascua Su\u00e1rez''' (born 21 March 1983) is a Spanish [[basketball]] [[Center (basketball)|center]].<ref>[http://basketball.eurobasket.com/player/Lucila_Pascua/79989|publisher=eurobasket.com] Profile in Eurobasket.com</ref>\n\nShe is a member of the [[Spain women's national basketball team|Spanish national team]], with whom she participated in the Olympic Games of [[Basketball at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's team squads|Athens 2004]], [[Basketball at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's team rosters|Beijing 2008]], and [[Basketball at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's team rosters|Rio 2016]], achieving a silver medal in the latter. She is one of the few players with more than 200 caps with Spain,<ref>[http://seleccionfemenina.feb.es/jugadoras.aspx List of Spanish National Team appearances in FEB.es]</ref><ref>[http://www.feb.es/2015/5/28/baloncesto/pascua-dominguez-homenajeadas/59641.aspx Pascua y Dom\u00ednguez homenajeadas (Spanish language)]</ref> and holds, together with [[Amaya Valdemoro]] and [[Laia Palau]], the record of participating in 4 [[FIBA World Championship for Women]] representing Spain, with whom she has earned silver and bronze medals.\n\nHaving played most of her career in several professional teams<ref>[http://competiciones.feb.es/estadisticas/Jugador.aspx?i=536360&c=1763642&med=0] Career stats in Liga Femenina</ref> in [[Liga Femenina de Baloncesto|Spain]], she signed with [[\u017dKK Novi Zagreb]] at the beginning of season 2013-2014. At the middle of the season she was released<ref>{{cite web |url=http://lovewomensbasketball.com/2014/01/07/pinkk-pecsi-424-signs-lucila-pascua-releases-janka-mincikova |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-10-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20141017114854/http://lovewomensbasketball.com/2014/01/07/pinkk-pecsi-424-signs-lucila-pascua-releases-janka-mincikova |archivedate=2014-10-17 }} PINKK Pecsi 424 signs Lucila Pascua</ref> and moved to [[PINKK-P\u00e9csi 424]] with whom she won the Hungarian League. She returned to Spain to play for [[CB Conquero]] during season 2014-2015. Since February 2019 she is at [[AE Sedis B\u00e0squet]].\n\n== Club career ==\nPascua started playing at age 9, at home club in [[Ripollet]], and continued her formation at [[Club Nataci\u00f3 Sabadell (basketball)|CN Sabadell]]. She then joined [[Segle XXI]], a project of the [[Catalonia|Catalan]] Federation for young prospects. She made her debut in the [[Liga Femenina de Baloncesto|Spanish League]] with [[CDB Zaragoza|Mann Filter]] at 18. In the following four years, she was chosen as Best Center in the 2002-03 league, participated in the [[EuroCup Women|2003-04 Eurocup Women]] and was [[Copa de la Reina de Baloncesto|Spanish Cup]] runner-up in 2005. \nShe spent the next four seasons at [[CB San Jos\u00e9]], participating in the [[Eurocup Women]] and again Spanish Cup runner-up in 2008. After two more years at Mann Filter, she signed for the [[2010\u201311 EuroLeague Women|2010-11 Euroleague]] champions [[CB Avenida|Perfumer\u00edas Avenida]], where she went to win the 2012 Cup and the 2013 League.\n\nShe spent the 2013-14 season abroad, first at [[Croatia]]n team [[ZKK Novi Zagreb]] and then at [[Hungary|Hungarian]] team [[PINKK-P\u00e9csi 424]], winning the [[Nemzeti Bajnoks\u00e1g I/A (women's basketball)|Hungarian League]]. Back in Spain, she spent two seasons at [[CB Conquero]], winning the 2016 Spanish Cup. Two days after winning the Cup, she was released by the club,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbconquero.es/2016/02/09/acuerdo-de-rescision-del-contrato-con-lucila-pascua/|title=Acuerdo de rescisi\u00f3n del contrato con Lucila Pascua|date=2016-02-09|work=Club Baloncesto Conquero|access-date=2017-09-30|language=es-ES|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160216174928/http://www.cbconquero.es/2016/02/09/acuerdo-de-rescision-del-contrato-con-lucila-pascua/|archive-date=2016-02-16|url-status=dead}}</ref> looking to get more playtime for the incoming [[2016 FIBA World Olympic Qualifying Tournament for Women|2016 Olympic Qualifying Tournament]]. She ended the season at Mann Filter, thus starting her third stint at Zaragoza. In November 2016, she became the League's all-time top rebounder<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://ligadia.feb.es/2016/11/6/baloncesto/luci-pascua-amplia-leyenda-convierte-maxima-reboteadora/67299.aspx|title=Luci Pascua ampl\u00eda su leyenda y se convierte en la m\u00e1xima reboteadora|work=ligafemenina.es|access-date=2017-09-30}}</ref> with 2,510 rebounds, surpassing [[\u00c9rika de Souza]].\n\n== National team ==\nShe made her debut with [[Spain women's national basketball team]] at the age of 18. She has played with the senior team since 2001. She is one of the most capped players with a total of 244 caps and 3.7 PPG.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://seleccionfemenina.feb.es/|title=Selecci\u00f3n Espa\u00f1ola Absoluta Femenina de Baloncesto|website=seleccionfemenina.feb.es|access-date=2017-09-30}}</ref>  She participated in three Olympic Games ([[Basketball at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|Athens 2004]], [[Basketball at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|Beijing 2008]] and [[Basketball at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|Rio 2016]]), four [[FIBA Women's Basketball World Cup|World Championships]] and six [[EuroBasket Women|European Championships]]:\n\n*[[File:Gold medal icon.svg|16px]] [[1999 FIBA Europe Under-16 Championship for Women]] (''youth'')\n*5th [[2002 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship for Women]] (''youth'')\n*5th [[2002 FIBA World Championship for Women|2002 World Championship]]\n*[[File:Bronze_medal_europe.svg|16x16px]] [[EuroBasket 2003 Women|2003 Eurobasket]]\n*6th [[Basketball at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|2004 Summer Olympics]]\n*[[File:Bronze_medal_europe.svg|16x16px]] [[EuroBasket Women 2005|2005 Eurobasket]]\n*8th [[2006 FIBA World Championship for Women|2006 World Championship]]\n*[[File:Silver_medal_europe.svg|16x16px]] [[EuroBasket 2007 Women|2007 Eurobasket]]\n*5th [[Basketball at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|2008 Summer Olympics]]\n*[[File:Bronze_medal_europe.svg|16x16px]] [[EuroBasket Women 2009|2009 Eurobasket]]\n*[[File:Bronze_medal_world_centered-2.svg|16x16px]] [[2010 FIBA World Championship for Women|2010 World Championship]]\n*9th [[EuroBasket Women 2011|2011 Eurobasket]]\n*[[File:Silver_medal_world_centered-2.svg|16x16px]] [[2014 FIBA World Championship for Women|2014 World Championship]]\n*[[File:Bronze_medal_europe.svg|16x16px]] [[EuroBasket Women 2015|2015 Eurobasket]]\n*[[File:Silver_medal_olympic.svg|16x16px]] [[Basketball at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|2016 Summer Olympics]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Spain squads\n| bg = #DB000D\n| fg = #FBEA0E\n| bordercolor = Black\n| list1 =\n{{Spain Squad 2010 FIBA World Championship for Women}}\n{{Spain Squad 2014 FIBA World Championship for Women}}\n{{Spain Women Basketball Squad 2016 Summer Olympics}}\n}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pascua, Lucila}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Sabadell]]\n[[Category:Spanish women's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Catalan women's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Olympic basketball players of Spain]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 2004 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Centers (basketball)]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Barcelona]]\n[[Category:\u017dKK Novi Zagreb players]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in Hungary]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists for Spain]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in basketball]]\n[[Category:Expatriate basketball people in Croatia]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in Croatia]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean Games bronze medalists for Spain]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean Games medalists in basketball]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 2001 Mediterranean Games]]\n", "text_old": "{{spanish name 2|Pascua|Su\u00e1rez}} \n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name               = Lucila Pascua\n| image              = Lucila Pascua.JPG\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Lucila Pascua in a game with [[CB Conquero]]\n| number             = 13\n| position           = [[Center (basketball)|Center]]\n| height_m           = 1.96\n| height_ft          = 6\n| height_in          = 5\n| league             = [[Liga Femenina de Baloncesto|Liga Femenina]]\n| team               = Mann Filter\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1983|3|21}}\n| birth_place        = [[Ripollet]], Spain\n| nationality        = Spanish\n| career_start       = 2001 \n| career_end         = \n| years1             = 2001\u20132005 \n| team1              = [[CDB Zaragoza|Mann Filter Zaragoza]]\n| years2             = 2005\u20132009 \n| team2              = [[CB San Jos\u00e9 Le\u00f3n]]\n| y