{"title_page": "George Seton, Lord Seton", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2013}}\n'''George Seton, Lord Seton, Master of Winton''' (15 May 1613 \u2013 4 June 1648) was the eldest surviving son of [[George Seton, 3rd Earl of Winton]], and continued the family's long-standing [[Roman Catholic]] traditions. Through his father's influence, in 1639 he married Lady Henrietta Gordon, daughter of the [[George Gordon, 2nd Marquess of Huntly|Marquess of Huntly]], with whom he made a great match and by whom he had four sons, of whom George succeeded his grandfather as Fourth Earl of Winton, and the others died young or without issue.\n\nSeton showed great military abilities and was firmly attached to the [[Cavalier|Royalist]] cause.  \n\nThe family estates flourished under his [[stewardship]], his father providing many opportunities to learn and excel at managing the family affairs, during the many troubles of the 17th century. Seton suffered great hardships at the hands of the rebels during the [[English Civil War]], and his father had to sell long-held family estates in [[Linlithgowshire]], that of [[Niddry Castle]] and one at [[Winchburgh]], to rescue him from imprisonment. He died at Seton on 4 June 1648, prematurely and unexpectedly of an illness probably caused by his imprisonment, predeceasing his father. Seton's son [[George Seton, 4th Earl of Winton|George]] thus succeeded his grandfather and became the 4th Earl.\n\nSeton's [[coat of arms]] appears in a large memorial window to the great [[James Graham, 1st Marquess of Montrose|Marquess of Montrose]] in [[St Giles' Cathedral]], [[Edinburgh]], as Seton was a prominent companion of that illustrious Royalist commander.\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book|author=Sir Bernard Burke|title=A Genealogical History of the Dormant: Abeyant, Forfeited, and Extinct Peerages of the British Empire|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K3MaAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA486|year=1866|publisher=Harrison|page=486}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Seton, George, Lord Seton, Master of Winton}}\n[[Category:1613 births]]\n[[Category:1648 deaths]]\n[[Category:Heirs apparent who never acceded]]\n[[Category:British courtesy barons and lords of Parliament]]\n\n\n{{UK-noble-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2013}}\n'''George Seton, Lord Seton, Master of Winton''' (15 May 1613 \u2013 4 June 1648) was the eldest surviving son of [[George Seton, 3rd Earl of Winton]], and continued the family's long-standing [[Roman Catholic]] traditions. Through his father's influence, in 1639 he married Lady Henrietta Gordon, daughter of the [[George Gordon, 1st Marquess of Huntly|Marquess of Huntly]], with whom he made a great match and by whom he had four sons, of whom George succeeded his grandfather as Fourth Earl of Winton, and the others died young or without issue.\n\nSeton showed great military abilities and was firmly attached to the [[Cavalier|Royalist]] cause.  \n\nThe family estates flourished under his [[stewardship]], his father providing many opportunities to learn and excel at managing the family affairs, during the many troubles of the 17th century. Seton suffered great hardships at the hands of the rebels during the [[English Civil War]], and his father had to sell long-held family estates in [[Linlithgowshire]], that of [[Niddry Castle]] and one at [[Winchburgh]], to rescue him from imprisonment. He died at Seton on 4 June 1648, prematurely and unexpectedly of an illness probably caused by his imprisonment, predeceasing his father. Seton's son [[George Seton, 4th Earl of Winton|George]] thus succeeded his grandfather and became the 4th Earl.\n\nSeton's [[coat of arms]] appears in a large memorial window to the great [[James Graham, 1st Marquess of Montrose|Marquess of Montrose]] in [[St Giles' Cathedral]], [[Edinburgh]], as Seton was a prominent companion of that illustrious Royalist commander.\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book|author=Sir Bernard Burke|title=A Genealogical History of the Dormant: Abeyant, Forfeited, and Extinct Peerages of the British Empire|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K3MaAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA486|year=1866|publisher=Harrison|page=486}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Seton, George, Lord Seton, Master of Winton}}\n[[Category:1613 births]]\n[[Category:1648 deaths]]\n[[Category:Heirs apparent who never acceded]]\n[[Category:British courtesy barons and lords of Parliament]]\n\n\n{{UK-noble-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Seton,_Lord_Seton"}
